### Phase 5: End-to-End Latency Measurement

**Goal:** Measure total system latency

#### Method 1: High-Speed Camera (Most Accurate)
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# test_end_to_end_latency.sh - End-to-end latency test

VR_HEADSET_IP="192.168.1.100"
RESOLUTION="3840x1080"
CODEC="h264_nvenc"
PRESET="p1"
BITRATE="15M"

echo "============================================"
echo "End-to-End Latency Test"
echo "============================================"
echo ""
echo "Setup Instructions:"
echo "1. Point robot cameras at a millisecond timer display"
echo "2. On VR headset, run the decoder:"
echo "   ffplay -fflags nobuffer -flags low_delay -framedrop udp://0.0.0.0:5000"
echo "3. Use a high-speed camera (240fps+) to record both:"
echo "   - The timer display (source)"
echo "   - The VR headset display (output)"
echo "4. Calculate: Latency = VR_time - Source_time"
echo ""
read -p "Press Enter when ready to start streaming..."

# Start streaming
ffmpeg -f v4l2 -framerate 90 -video_size 1920x1080 -i /dev/video0 \
  -f v4l2 -framerate 90 -video_size 1920x1080 -i /dev/video2 \
  -filter_complex "[0:v][1:v]hstack" \
  -c:v ${CODEC} -preset ${PRESET} -tune ll \
  -b:v ${BITRATE} -maxrate ${BITRATE} -minrate ${BITRATE} \
  -g 12 -bf 0 \
  -f mpegts udp://${VR_HEADSET_IP}:5000

echo ""
echo "Streaming started. Perform latency measurement with high-speed camera."
echo "Press Ctrl+C to stop."
```

#### Method 2: Software Timer Overlay
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# stream_with_timer.sh - Stream with millisecond timer overlay

VR_HEADSET_IP="192.168.1.100"
RESOLUTION="3840x1080"
CODEC="h264_nvenc"
PRESET="p1"
BITRATE="15M"

echo "Starting stream with timer overlay..."
echo "On VR headset, run: ffplay -fflags nobuffer -flags low_delay -framedrop udp://0.0.0.0:5000"
echo ""

ffmpeg -f v4l2 -framerate 90 -video_size 1920x1080 -i /dev/video0 \
  -f v4l2 -framerate 90 -video_size 1920x1080 -i /dev/video2 \
  -filter_complex "[0:v][1:v]hstack,drawtext=fontfile=/usr/share/fonts/truetype/dejavu/DejaVuSans-Bold.ttf:text='%{pts\:hms}':fontsize=72:fontcolor=white:box=1:boxcolor=black@0.5:x=10:y=10" \
  -c:v ${CODEC} -preset ${PRESET} -tune ll \
  -b:v ${BITRATE} -maxrate ${BITRATE} -minrate ${BITRATE} \
  -g 12 -bf 0 \
  -f mpegts udp://${VR_HEADSET_IP}:5000
```

#### Method 3: Loopback Test (Automated)
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# test_loopback_latency.sh - Automated loopback latency test

echo "Loopback Latency Test"
echo "This will point the camera at its own output to measure round-trip latency"
echo "Measured latency will be 2x actual one-way latency"
echo ""
echo "Setup: Point robot camera at monitor displaying VR output"
read -p "Press Enter when ready..."

# Create timestamp overlay and loopback test
# Note: This requires manual measurement or computer vision to detect timestamp
echo "Manual measurement required - record both displays and calculate difference"
```

**Latency Measurement Table:**

| Component | Budget (ms) | Measured (ms) | Notes |
|-----------|-------------|---------------|-------|
| Camera capture | ~1 | | From camera specs |
| Encoding | <11 | | From Phase 1 results |
| Network (one-way) | <15 | | From Phase 4 (RTT/2) |
| Decoding | <8 | | Estimated from hardware |
| VR display pipeline | <6 | | VR headset processing |
| **TOTAL** | **<40** | | Sum of all components |

